<br>
The problem with cheal is this: it's mana/hp ratio will continually improve as the game grows. You can't balance spells out and balance encounters out properly when the thing you are balancing against is constantly increasing unless you create mobs who are also constantly increasing in effectiveness or zones that are always growing in difficulty. Cheal + time = work for verant.<br>
<br>
As the game gets older, if cheal remains (and it will because the retooling you would have to do if you removed it is basically 2 full expansions), you will see other healing spells created to keep druids and shaman from being laughable because cheal can now heal for it's full amount as mudflation has given tanks 10k hp.<br>
<br>
It's not a bitch from me tho, Baps. It's just the state of the game. Velious and Luclin would not be what they were if there was no cheal so it's not really possible to say what the state of the game would be if it never existed.<br>
<br>
The only way to make cheal slide back into balance without having to revamp the whole damn game is to assign it's mana cost based on the hit points it heals. Find the best other ratio heal spell in the game (is it torpor ?) and then give cheal the same cost ratio, maybe 25% of a better ratio since it's so definitive, and then put in a class aa for clerics to make it a smidgeon better.<br>
<br>
That, or just hope that the eq2 spell engine doesn't have preset ratios in the form of spells that will become obsolete because of mudflation. Instead, define spellcost as a ratio to hit points healed (or nuked for), with multipliers for casting time, recast time, and reagent usage and let players decide how to make the spells they want to use. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uanikacrystalwind.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Anika Crystalwind</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Admin Gnome</span><br>  Posts: 1151<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/9/02 2:13:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=29>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 10k hp tanks</span><hr size=1> Baldrik is right, there's a huge difference between a CHeal chain and a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> good</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> CHeal chain.  Smacking a button every 12 seconds is the ideal scenario, but there's a LOT of external influences that can throw wrenches into that perfect world, and learning to adapt on-the-fly takes practice.  6 months ago, PO's CHeal chains were pathetic as well - just like anything, keeping a tank up takes practice.<br>
